<hl>
<seg id=1> The Japanese Prime Minister hoped Kiichi Migazawa would remain in office, and carry out the economic recovery plan. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Reuters, Tokyo Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Migazawa received pressure to remain in office yesterday. </seg>
<seg id=3> Last week, he announced that he wanted to resign soon. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Whether Kiichi Migazawa remained in office or not made the united government of the Liberal Democratic Party (Shizuka Kamei) and the Social Democratic Party (Takato Doi) covered with a layer of shade. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> High officials' open disagreement on cabinet positions in the Social Democratic Party made the united government unstable. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It's known to the external world that after Kiichi Migazawa resigned, General Secretary of the Social Democratic Party Masajuro Shiokawa would replace him. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Last Friday, Kiichi Migazawa expressed that he might resign before the end of the year, but he didn't state the exact date. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> At a journalists' conference, he said: "I can't tell you the date"." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> It's supposed that he would remain in office until the end of the two-week special meeting of the Congress. </seg>
<seg id=10> The meeting of the Congress would end on 14 December. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Koizumi's Vice-Cabinet Secretary Teijiro Furukawa told the Japanese Broadcasting Association TV Station that he believed that the Prime Minister wanted 79-year-old Kiichi Migazawa to remain in office. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Teijiro said: "I think (Koizumi) hoped he would remain in office in private, and carry out the economic recovery plan." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Koizumi would talk with Kiichi Migazawa. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> He said:" Considering his ability, it's difficult to replace him. </seg>
<seg id=15> I myself wish him to remain in office as well to vigorously develop the national economy." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=16> Koizumi read the reports on Kiichi Migazawa's resignation, and he was going to talk with him. </seg>
</p>
